rmandie, Frankrijk","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Beauchamp, Calcados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Basse-Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"abt 0966–1045":"about 0966–1045","0950–1008":"0950–1008","0984–Female":"0984–Deceased","1007–1068":"1007–1068","0966–1045":"0966–1045","1008":"1008","1007":"1007","0950":"0950","0984":"0984","abt 0966":"about 0966","1068":"1068","1045":"1045","0966":"0966","Normandie, France":"Normandy, France","Pont-Audemer, Eure, Haute Normandie, France":"Pont-Audemer, Eure, Upper Normandy, France","France":"France","Vielles, Normandie, France":"Normandy, France","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","Beauchamp, Calcados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Lower Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Haie","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Haw  .","Irish (Kilkenny): variant of   Haugh  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Haw","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Haw(e)</i> which, like <i>Daw(e)</i>, was probably a rhyming pet form of Middle English <i>Raw</i> (Ralph). Similar rhyming pet forms of other Anglo-Norman male personal names beginning with <i>R-</i> are found in <i>Hick</i> and <i>Dick</i> for <i>Rick</i> (Richard) and <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i> for <i>Rob(ert)</i>. See also   Hawkin  .","English: topographic name for someone who lived by an enclosure, from Middle English <i>hawe</i> ‘enclosure’ (Old English <i>haga</i> or Old Norse <i>hagi</i>). Compare   Haugh  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 何 and 賀, see   He   1 and 2."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda Haie was born about 0966, in France. She married Hugh II de Beauchamp in Normandy, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1045, in Pont-Audemer, Eure, Upper Normandy, France, at the age of 80."},"et":{"abt 0966–1045":"umbes 0966–1045","0950–1008":"0950–1008","0984–Female":"0984–Surnud","1007–1068":"1007–1068","0966–1045":"0966–1045","1008":"1008","1007":"1007","0950":"0950","0984":"0984","abt 0966":"umbes 0966","1068":"1068","1045":"1045","0966":"0966","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Pont-Audemer, Eure, Haute Normandie, France":"Pont-Audemer, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa","Vielles, Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Beauchamp, Calcados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"abt 0966–1045":"noin 0966–1045","0950–1008":"0950–1008"